# Short-link redirects for SMS / email engagement tracking.
#
# Customer taps lotlinkin.com/v/<vehicleShort>?c=<contactShort> in an SMS
# from Jordan. Netlify 302's the path to the BDC API, which logs the click
# (vehicle_link_clicks table) and then 302's to the dealer's VDP page.
# Two hops, both fast, both transparent to the customer.
#
# The :splat placeholder forwards everything after /v/ including query
# string. The :splat reference in the destination expands to that.
# 302 (not 301) because we want browsers to re-resolve every time —
# stops vehicle URLs from getting cached if the destination changes.
/v/*  https://lotlink-api-production.up.railway.app/v/:splat  302

# 2026-06-21: Dynamic QR short-links for printed collateral. The QR codes
# printed on cards/flyers encode a FIXED short path (e.g. /card); the
# destination below is what we can change anytime WITHOUT reprinting.
# Always 302 (never 301) so browsers re-resolve every scan — a 301 would
# cache permanently and defeat the whole point of a dynamic QR.
# One slug per medium so we can repoint (and later track) each separately.
/card    /demo  302
/flyer   /demo  302

# 2026-05-28: Concierge / marketplace pivot is complete. The site is
# now SaaS-only (AI BDC for independent dealers). These four pages were
# the consumer-buyer / marketplace-dealer artifacts; redirect any
# leftover inbound traffic (Google index, social links, old SMS) to the
# homepage with a permanent 301 so search engines drop them from the
# index over the next few crawls. Trailing-slash variants included
# because Netlify treats them as distinct paths.
/concierge.html  /  301
/concierge       /  301
/concierge/      /  301
/dealers.html    /  301
/dealers         /  301
/dealers/        /  301
/vehicle.html    /  301
/vehicle         /  301
/vehicle/        /  301
/inventory.html  /  301
/inventory       /  301
/inventory/      /  301
